<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 8:7<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I27da1d50630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>8.</label.designator><headtext>Relevancy</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71fc90c682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>8:7.</label.designator><headtext>Proving general good and bad character of parties</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>As a general rule, evidence of a person&apos;s character is inadmissible. <eos/><bos/>Under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-4-405" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Iea2f161074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-4-405</cite.query>, a witness may offer reputation or opinion testimony in all cases where evidence of character is admissible and where character is an essential element.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In federal practice, as in Georgia law, other acts evidence is only admissible if relevant for some noncharacter purpose[<footnote.reference refid="I79151e1074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] or if character is an “essential issue” in the case.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7915452074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] Application of the character rule in federal civil cases is similar to Georgia practice, but it is advisable to check each specific area and the particular federal circuit case law for different applications of the general rule.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7915452174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-4-405" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Iea35ccd074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-4-405</cite.query><?page no="237"?> provides:</paratext><codes.excerpt ID="I28179b80630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><codes.subsection ID="I28179b81630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><codes.para><head parent="codes.para"><label.designator>(a)</label.designator></head><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>In all proceedings in which evidence of character or a trait of character of a person is admissible, proof shall be made by testimony as to reputation or by testimony in the form of an opinion.<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext></codes.para></codes.subsection><codes.subsection ID="I2817c290630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><codes.para><head parent="codes.para"><label.designator>(b)</label.designator></head><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>In proceedings in which character or a trait of character of a person is an essential element of a charge, claim, or defense or when an accused testifies to his or her own character, proof may also be made of specific instances of that person&apos;s conduct. <eos/><bos/>The character of the accused, including specific instances of the accused&apos;s conduct, shall also be admissible in a presentencing hearing subject to the provisions of <cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-10-2" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Iea36902074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Code Section 17-10-2</cite.query>.<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/></paratext></codes.para></codes.subsection><codes.subsection ID="I2817e9a0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><codes.para><head parent="codes.para"><label.designator>(c)</label.designator></head><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>On cross-examination, inquiry shall be allowable into relevant specific instances of conduct.<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0003"/></paratext></codes.para></codes.subsection></codes.excerpt><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Thus, when a witness testifies about a defendant&apos;s good character, the state may cross-examine that witness about the defendant&apos;s prior misconduct in an attempt to undermine the witness&apos;s credibility.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7915452274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] Moreover, the cross-examination may include specific instances of conduct which include prior arrests or convictions of the defendant.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I79156c3074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Historically, Georgia law restricted evidence of good or bad character to a party&apos;s reputation in the community,[<footnote.reference refid="I79156c3174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] and evidence of good or bad character could not be shown on direct examination by specific acts.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I79156c3274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] However, on cross-examination, a witness who testified to the good or bad reputation of a party could be questioned regarding specific acts of that party to test the foundation of the witness&apos; testimony.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I79156c3374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] The “community” where a party&apos;s reputation was gained included both the area where he lived and where he worked.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I79156c3474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>] To introduce character evidence, the witness would describe how he knows the party, if the party&apos;s reputation in the community is one of good or bad character,[<footnote.reference refid="I79156c3574d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>] and the party&apos;s character and reputation, such as his reputation for violence[<footnote.reference refid="I79156c3674d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>] or honesty,[<footnote.reference refid="I7915934074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference>] as it relates to specific issues in the case. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="1979146325" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iea3aaed274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Simpkins v. State</ital></cite.query><?page no="238"?>, witnesses could testify that they knew the party and that no one within the knowledge of the witness had spoken ill of the character of the party.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7915934174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">13</footnote.reference>] The new Evidence Code now allows opinion testimony as well.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7915934274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">14</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER405" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Iea3b722074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Fed. R. Evid. 405</cite.query> controls the methods of proving character evidence in federal courts.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I79151e1074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See, e.g., <cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="2014754356" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="Iea31ae2174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Goldsmith v. Bagby Elevator Co., Inc., 513 F.3d 1261, 75 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 601 (11th Cir. 2008)</cite.query> (evidence of discrimination against other employees admitted under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER404" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Iea31ae2574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Rule 404(b)</cite.query> to show motive, intent, or plan).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7915452074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See, e.g., <cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="1998122423" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="Iea32717174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Schafer v. Time, Inc., 142 F.3d 1361, 49 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 911 (11th Cir. 1998)</cite.query> (action for defamation or libel).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7915452174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Each federal circuit has announced its own test for admitting other bad acts evidence under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER404" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Iea3557a774d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Rule 404(b)</cite.query><?page no="237"?>. <eos/><bos/>See Goode and Wellborn, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="ER" w-normalized-cite="CTHBFEDEVIDRule404" w-pub-number="0165499" ID="Iea3557a074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Courtroom Handbook on Federal Evidence, Rule 404(a) (2012 ed.)</cite.query> Regarding the Eleventh Circuit rule, see <cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="2008577958" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="Iea3557a374d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">U.S. v. LeCroy, 441 F.3d 914, 69 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 669 (11th Cir. 2006)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7915452274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="2044475559" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iea37055274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Leanos v. State, 303 Ga. 666, 814 S.E.2d 332 (2018)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79156c3074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="2048347172" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iea37537174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Montgomery v. State, 828 S.E.2d 620 (Ga. Ct. App. 2019)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79156c3174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="1980115264" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iea37c8a274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Smith v. State, 153 Ga. App. 519, 265 S.E.2d 852 (1980)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79156c3274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="1963125908" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iea383dd274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Taylor v. Marsh, 107 Ga. App. 575, 130 S.E.2d 770 (1963)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>This rule holds true; see <cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="2036450466" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iea383dd574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Mohamud v. State, 297 Ga. 532, 773 S.E.2d 755 (2015)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79156c3374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="1980148631" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iea388bf274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Curry v. State, 155 Ga. App. 829, 273 S.E.2d 411 (1980)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79156c3474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="1979127179" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iea39012274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Bush v. State, 149 Ga. App. 448, 254 S.E.2d 453 (1979)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79156c3574d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="1965125744" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iea394f4274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Gravitt v. State, 220 Ga. 781, 141 S.E.2d 893 (1965)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79156c3674d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="1908012249" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="Iea399d6274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Arnold v. State, 131 Ga. 494, 496, 62 S.E. 806 (1908)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7915934074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="1855002068" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" w-pinpoint-page="496" ID="Iea39eb8174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">McNabb v. Lockhart, 18 Ga. 495, 496, 1855 WL 1715 (1855)</cite.query><?page no="238"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7915934174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>13</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-serial-number="1979146325" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iea3ad5e274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Simpkins v. State, 149 Ga. App. 763, 766, 256 S.E.2d 63 (1979)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7915934274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>14</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017132" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-4-405" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Iea3b240074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-4-405(a)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 8:7<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
